      <div class="col-lg-3">
        <h1> The Architect </h1>
        <p>
          Ricardo Legorreta was a prolific Mexican architect who trained at the National University of Mexico. His signature style was a mix of Mexico’s indigenous and colonial sensibilities with modern simplicity. A dear friend of Luis Barragan, Legorreta employed the same simple and auter base of simple shapes to maximize the emotional connection of the structure, but then added bright color and dynamic lighting capacity back into Mexican architecture.
        </p>
        <p>
          Legorreta was entirely an emotional designer, believing structured design would gut the structure of the necessary character. He would not draft until he had already arrived at the shape of the structure. Elements and colors would be added simply because he felt it was necessary. Necessities and intricacies would be added by later drafters after the shape had already been established.
        </p>
        <p>
          Legorreta received the American Institute of Architects Gold Medal in 2000 and the Praemium Imperiale arts prize of Japan in 2011. He passed away on December 30, 2011 at the age of 80. His firm, Legorreta + Legorreta, is continued by his son Victor, who continues to expound on the styles of his father in modern settings.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-9">
        <h1> The Interior </h1>
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-3">
            <img src="./images/Interior-Atrium.jpg" class="img-fluid">
            <p>
              The six-story central yellow central atrium not only draws visitors into the massive centor space, but also excellently uses repeating vertical lines to increase the sense of height and uses the diffusion of the light to add character to the otherwise flat walls.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-3">
            <img src="./images/Interior-Computer-Usage.jpg" class="img-fluid">
            <p>
              The practicalities of the structure ar estill respected by the shift white and wooden walls near computer work stations which are not confident to claustrophobic spaces.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-3">
            <img src="./images/Interior-Stacks.jpg" class="img-fluid">
            <p>
              The building excellently uses indirect natural light aligned with the stacks to allow soft, natural light to illuminate as much of the building as possible.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-3">
            <img src="./images/Interior-Work-Space.jpg" class="img-fluid">
            <p>
              The layout of floors creates high ceilings for even mundane workstations, creating a dynamic surrounding for an otherwise grounded workstation.
            </p>
          </div>
