      <div class="col-lg-3">
        <h1>Blog Post</h1>
        <p> The “Project for Public Spaces” hosts a database of case studies called the “Hall of Shame Archive,” which documents complaints against local public spaces. One of these was logged against the San Antonio Public Library.</p>
        <p> The post, which can be read in full here, brings to light two implications: </p>
        <ul>
          <li> The building is hostile to those who approach by bus or pedestrians, as there is a single main entrance.</li>
          <li>The structures distinctive style separates it from the rest of San Antonio. </li>
        </ul>
        <p> The authors points about logistics difficulties are well taken. The building is very much oriented toward its parking lot, and seems to disregard the long road along the north side. However, the buses likely have to stop in this inconvenient location because of the realities of the road.</p>
        <p> The distinction of the building certainly does abruptly separate it from the rest of downtown, and perhaps purposefully so. The architecture is inherently Mexican, unlike the southwestern blend that is usual in the rest of San Antonio. Whether this is representative of changing times or disrespectful of location is an opinion probably driven by debates of identity.</p>
        <p> Overall, I can understand the concerns of this author, but disagree with the severity. Cosmopolitan cities are a collection of odd-balls, not uniformities.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-12">
        <h1> Summary </h1>
        <p> The San Antonio Central Library was a bold move by the city, which brought a visually eccentric building to the downtown image. The building gathered controversy for its outward appearance, but succeeded in almost every demanded capacity. It not only increased readership, but created new spaces for students of all ages to learn. The building has become an icon not just of books, but of learning and adaptation to changing times.</p>
        <p> These are certainly important qualities. Libraries are in many places a dying public space., yet projects such as this one, and the much newer Austin Central Library defy the trend. </p>
        <p> Perhaps the need for libraries is best summarized by Annie Spence, a Detroit Librarian, speaking to this American Life:</p>
        <div class="inset">
          <p> “I always say that it's the only place-- well, it's one of the last places you can go that you don't have to buy or believe in anything to come in. You can just come, and we'll help you, no matter what your question is. We'll try to figure it out with you.” </p>
        </div>

